##I'm in a intensive-care unit

Wechat, renwumag1980

Feature Introduction, the best Chinese character report

Walking into Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital, the first feeling is quiet. Unlike the other three top hospitals in the downtown area of Wuhan, this Special Hospital for infectious diseases, with its far-off buildings and trees, is lush even in winter. The doors and windows of the COVID-19, the building where hundreds of pneumonia patients had been admitted, were closed and barely audible from the ground floor. Because the patient does not need a family member to accompany, also nobody moves along on the road.

But below the silence was a constant battle, in the intensive care units on the fifth and seventh floors of the South Wing of the inpatient department, with increased oxygen, many rescues a day, and the fear of infection among the staff. In Wuhan's epidemic situation, the gold and Silver Pool Hospital takes the first batch of fixed-point admission patient's hospital, is the battle first scene.
Since late January, medical teams from Shanghai, Beijing, Army Medical University and Hunan have entered Jinyintan hospital to support patients'medical and nursing work. In the ICU, doctors and nurses from all over work together. On January 27, Central South University sent the first medical team, including five nurses from the Department of Critical Care Medicine, to help patients with "continuous blood purification treatment" in the intensive-care unit of the hospital. This treatment, commonly known as "hemodialysis" , can remove impurities from the patient's body. Because multiple organ dysfunction syndrome pneumonia can cause heart disease, dialysis can extend the time patients need to be treated, allowing them to continue waiting for better drugs and treatments. Three of the nurses, Zhang Chunyan, Zhu Lian and Li Xiang, told people about their experiences at intensive-care unit on Feb. 1.
Here's what they said:

Unlike the other three top hospitals in the downtown area of Wuhan, this Special Hospital for infectious diseases, with its far-off buildings and trees, is lush even in winter. In the ICU, doctors and nurses from all over work together. On January 27, Central South University sent the first medical team, including five nurses from the Department of Critical Care Medicine, to help patients with "continuous blood purification treatment" in the intensive-care unit of the hospital. This treatment, commonly known as "hemodialysis" , can remove impurities from the patient's body. Because multiple organ dysfunction syndrome pneumonia can cause heart disease, dialysis can extend the time patients need to be treated, allowing them to continue waiting for better drugs and treatments. Three of the nurses, Zhang Chunyan, Zhu Lian and Li Xiang, told people about their experiences at intensive-care unit on Feb. 1.

Here's what they said:

By Luo Ting

Editor, sugar maple

1

January 28th was the first day of our clinical practice at the Golden Pool Hospital. The Ward we are in charge of is on the fifth, sixth and seventh floors of the South Building of the Inpatient Department of Jinyintan Hospital.

It takes half an hour just to get dressed before you enter the room, as if you're in a changing room, changing into your work clothes, passing through the doctor's office, and entering a buffer room where the doctors are dispensing medication and writing paperwork, this is where we wash our hands, wear masks, hats, wash our hands, wear protective clothing. And then you go into a buffer room, where you put on a waterproof suit and two shoe covers. Then there's the buffer room, where the usual staff on the outside hand us things. And ended up in the hospital room.

The first time I went into the intensive care unit, I didn't think it was anything else, but I didn't think it was going to be that tough. Because this is a temporary ward into the ICU, strictly speaking, only the patient's condition to meet the requirements of the ICU, Ward conditions did not meet.

A real intensive care unit is a large room where you can see everything about a patient at a glance. The facilities on the bed can also be connected in series, for example, I'm looking at the patient in bed one now, if the patient in bed two's vital signs are not good, I can also see it in bed one, there's a red light on the side of the bed that keeps flashing, tell me what's wrong with bed two. And this ICU, is a ward by Ward, each ward has two or three patients, have to rely on their own to find. You have to walk around all the time, you have to watch, you have to walk around, you have to walk around, you have to walk around, you have to walk around, you have to look around, you have to walk around, you have to walk around, you have to walk around, you have to walk around, you have to walk around, you have to. In a panic, no idea.

It's a tough situation for the patient. The oxygen here is not central oxygen, we need to push our own oxygen tanks, oxygen tanks are very big, very high, we have to use all our strength. And because the entire hospital is filled with confirmed patients, and there are no family members to accompany us, we handle six or seven patients alone, and I think they should be very afraid, too, to be isolated here, not like in a normal hospital, but at least have family members with them, or be able to go for a walk, in here, you just lie in bed and rest.

In the I.C.U. , or at least the patients we care for, are basically older, mostly in their 50s and 70s, and the basic lung condition itself isn't very good. I've had 29-year-olds and 40-year-olds, but they're not that sick. In most patients, it's dyspnea. The severity varies from person to person, depending on non invasive breathing and high flow rates, to intubation, to the most severe, and the use of extracorporeal lungs.

We found it very difficult to bear that they were two or three people in a room with no cover in the middle. Two-thirds of the patients were sedated and sleeping, but a third were awake and conscious. They will certainly witness the rescue of patients in the same ward. Sometimes the patient's breathing is so bad, the non-invasive machine can't support your Hoo Hoo, we're GONNA have to put in an artificial airway, put a tube through the patient's mouth, and sometimes do chest compressions.

The patients who were treated were suffering, and the patients in the same ward saw it, so we thought it must have been quite painful. I don't want them to see this, but I can't do it here. There's no curtain to keep them apart. They are very nice, people are very good, but we are all infected with the same virus, certainly psychological pressure, they did not show it, but we all know in our hearts, look also feel good sad.

Those patients are awake, just breathing hard, giving them a little more oxygen, they'll breathe easier. They were quiet. They wouldn't yell at us unless there was something really wrong. The most they talked to us was "thank you" , "I'm sorry" , "please" .

Once met a patient, 40-year-old, because there is no family around, stool and urine are rely on us to clean up. Every time you give him a Poo and a pee, he says, "I'm sorry. ". After hearing this, I didn't know what to say. He thinks you do all the dirty work, but for us intensive-care unit, it's our job, and I usually say, "it's okay. " . Even at this time, you can actually see a person's dignity and dignity.

The nurses used stickers on the glass to communicate with the outside world

2

In fact, after the first day of work, one of the three of us (Zhu love) cried.

First, the environment is quite strange, we simply do intensive care in Xiangya hospital, in fact, very little contact with this need to isolate the infectious patients, a large number of patients suffering from respiratory failure, may be fine one second, the next second has changed. So now the work is not the same rhythm as the original work, more heavy.

Plus, your partner is new here, you don't know each other, and the point you're talking to, the other person might not know. For example, in the rescue, who is responsible for pressing, who is responsible for spraying, who will record the rescue time, who ordered a team of people should be very clear division of Labor. But now everyone is wearing protective clothing, no one knows who, you just arrived, do not know where the rescue supplies are, and call for help, but others also have to manage six or seven patients, their own patients may not be in good condition. It's a lot of pressure to do these things in a panic and blindly.

During a 10-hour shift from 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. that day, I (Zhu Lian) had never worked for such a long time wearing a protective suit and N95. Really is the whole body sweat wet, the body is actually very uncomfortable, the most dangerous thing is, the mask was wet with sweat. And I thought, you know, theoretically, if you wet the mask, it wouldn't be so protective. When I feed and water a patient, it blows air out of the machine into my face, and my mask gets wet, which puts me at high risk of exposure, which puts me under a lot of stress. I went home and cried. Crying is better, the next day slowly adapted, now the mood has been quite stable.

Before I came here, I (Zhang Chunyan) was still worried. Because of the virus, I couldn't turn on the air conditioner all the time. It would be cold and sleepy. But in fact, in this closed and busy environment, I really wouldn't feel sleepy. Every time I was sweating profusely, i'd stand in the hallway, close my eyes, count to 10 seconds, and then I'd get to work.

To tell you the truth, we are medical personnel, volunteered to go to war, but also are the daughter of others, are ordinary people, are afraid of infection, but also experienced some of the more dangerous moment.

It was also the first day of work, when I (Zhang Chunyan) wearing glasses and mask, no mask, just a regular protection. After a long time inside, all the mask sweat, the glasses will be easy to fog. Fogging is a sign that you are not sealing well and gas will escape. We have a rule that glasses must be replaced as soon as they fog up.

But I was intubating a patient the other day, and the glasses were fogging up, and in that case you wouldn't have been able to adjust your hands because they were contaminated. I didn't want to replace it. Besides, if I did, there'd be no supplies, and you don't want to waste them. There are so few protective clothing, when you change it, it's face screen, protective clothing, N95. This matter has been pressing in my heart, never said it out, but the psychological pressure is still very big.

Not only these times, we help patients feed and water, handle stool and urine, rescue, has been in close contact with them. These patients often cough and sneeze, which can not be stopped. So if doctors are the front line, we're the super front line. We worked in the intensive-care unit, holding walkie talkies and talking to the outside. If we wanted anything, we'd put a note on the glass and they'd send it in.

So for us, there is no demand for food or shelter. The most worry, the most nervous, the most sensitive, is that the protective material can not keep up. We're not at the highest level of protection yet. The N95 is a two-ply, thin blue one, which isn't really what you're looking for. It's supposed to be a three-ply white N95. But there's a shortage. There's no such thing. Let's just keep our heads down.

After arriving here, we all cut our hair short and couldn't go to the barbershop, so we bought a pair of scissors in the supermarket and helped each other cut them. According to the regulations, after taking off the protective clothing, we had better wash our hair in the hospital, which must be shorter and more convenient and easier to dry, so we cut it off. But don't cut it too short. It needs to be tied up so the hat can cover it. If it is too short, it will be exposed from the side, and stick to the eyes, in fact, is a pollution.

Coming out of the ward, the whole process was complicated. Wearing the isolation clothes is actually good, take off more trouble, each take off a layer, you have to wash your hands. Each hand-washing action of more than 15 seconds, the process of hand-washing to reach 3 minutes, these days wash hands many times, long lost count.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The nurses are cutting each other's hair

3

This time, we all volunteered to come to golden pond hospital. At that time, the head nurse sent a message in the group, saying that the National Health Council needed five nurses with experience in critical care and who could perform continuous blood purification. We immediately signed up, and within half an hour we were full.

Some of us were at home in our pajamas, lying on the couch eating sunflower seeds, watching TV, and some were still shopping. Sign up for the news immediately said, let's get to the hospital in an hour, really only half an hour to pack. I don't know how long I've been here, I just packed up a little bit, and my dad didn't ask me for anything, so he just ran down and bought five boxes of instant noodles.

Central South University, a nurse from the Department of Critical Care Medicine at Central South University

When we get to the hospital, we'll train you on how to put on and off your Hazmat suit. Although we have been working in the Department of Critical Care Medicine in Xiangya for nearly ten years, we have never worn protective clothing for such a long time. Evening Training, the next day by high-speed rail to Wuhan, the third day to work.

A few years ago, during the Ebola epidemic, we also recruited, we all want to apply, but the rigid conditions are very high, the requirements are party members, English Level 6, in charge of nurses, at that time we are very young, did not meet these requirements. Ya'an earthquake is the same, want to sign up, not up to the standard. This time is different, we have worked so many years, a lot of experience, hope to be able to put their professional above things, to serve them. As a medical staff who do not want to contribute their own strength, just different posts. Our colleagues in Xiangya are also in the front line.

We don't think it's a big deal, but we're pretty careful about how we talk to our families. Do not video with their parents, for fear of video with them, they will ask this to ask that, ask oneself have emotions, so basically are talking about Wechat, give them a safe report. My (Zhu love) grandmother is old, nearly 80 years old, every time I talk to her on the phone, she will cry at the sound of my voice and feel sorry for me, working here is very hard, it will be painful, I also simply did not call later, just check in with the family group every day.

My (Zhang Chunyan) daughter still tells with my husband today, say mother how not to come back? I haven't seen her in a long time. We drove to pick her up. Because I used to go to work, my husband drove to pick me up every day, today she pulled my father, said to pick up my mother back. All I can do is video-chat with her every day, so she can see me every day.

When we left Changsha, we packed our bags in a hurry, expecting to stay for a month. But right now, we don't really know how long it's GonNa last. The biggest wish has two, one is that the protective material is sufficient. I was working the night shift the other night, and they told me that I couldn't go out at night because I didn't have enough protective clothing, so I took two big snickers bars and immediately poured them down, they were so greasy and sweet, but I had to eat a little bit, snickers bars are high in calories, they can endure, i'm afraid I won't last that long in there. Another hope is to quickly develop drugs, or effective treatments, to cure their diseases.

Originally we have always wanted to come to Wuhan to see the Cherry Blossoms, has not come, and now in a month or so, the Cherry blossoms will open. Hopefully the epidemic will be over by then, and after the Cherry Blossoms, we can all go home. This is the best.
